          en: "Coffee phenology tracks recurring biological events: vegetative growth, flower bud initiation, anthesis (flowering), fruit set, cherry development, and ripening. These stages correlate with environmental triggers—rainfall patterns, temperature, photoperiod—varying by origin and altitude. Understanding phenology enables farmers to: predict harvest timing, plan labor needs, schedule fertilization optimally, anticipate pest/disease pressure windows, and manage multiple fruiting cycles. In regions with bimodal rainfall (Kenya, Colombia), coffee produces two harvests annually with distinct phenological patterns. Climate change disrupts traditional phenology—flowering occurring at unusual times, uneven ripening, overlapping cycles—complicating management and reducing quality. Precision agriculture uses phenological monitoring (visual assessment, weather data, remote sensing) to optimize interventions. Proper phenological management directly impacts yield quantity, bean uniformity, and ultimately cup quality. It's fundamental agronomy for consistent, high-quality production.",
